userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use note
userestrict.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center has title, copyright, and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them, and has authority to grant permission to cite and publish archival material from the collection.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: This series is divided into 6 subseries:

Subseries 1 - General Correspondence, 1960-1970 Subseries 2 - State Files and Summaries, 1960-1970 Subseries 3 - Talent File, 1960-1970 Subseries 4 - Memos, 1959-1970 Subseries 5 - Correspondence, 1960-1968 Subseries 6 - Congressional Quarterly, 1960-1971.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains the office files of George L. Hinman. They document official activities in the execution of his duties as a member of Nelson Rockefeller's staff. For more information, refer to the Scope and Content Notes for the individual subseries. The actions, decisions, and exchanges of information or points of view documented here occurred in the course of proposing and implementing policies for the Rockefeller administration, political campaigns, or Rockefeller's personal activities. However, unless a document is personally signed by Nelson A. Rockefeller, or is referred to in a document personally signed by him, it should not be assumed he saw the document or was aware of its existence or substance. Furthermore, researchers should bear in mind that staff files may contain documents or drafts addressed to Rockefeller that were never shown to him.
Issues of the "Congressional Quarterly" from 1962 to 1971 are also available. Complete yearly runs exist for 1964 to 1967. Some issues were annotated by Mr. Hinman.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: George Lyon Hinman was born in Binghamton, New York. He graduated from Princeton University in 1927 and received a law degree from Harvard University in 1930. That same year he joined the law firm of Hinman, Howard & Kattell. He became partner and at one time headed the firm, with which he was still associated at that time of his death in 1997. Throughout his life, Hinman served on a variety of boards, including the New York State Board of Regents and the boards of Colgate University and IBM.

Hinman first came to Nelson A. Rockefeller's attention in 1956, when he was named as counsel to the Temporary State Commission to Prepare for a Constitutional Convention, which was chaired by Rockefeller. Two years later, after Rockefeller was elected Governor, Hinman became his executive assistant. From 1960 to 1977, Hinman held the title of special counsel, Rockefeller Family and Associates.

George Hinman was an important aide during Rockefeller's four terms as governor of New York, from 1959 to 1973, as well as throughout Rockefeller's tenure as U.S. Vice President under President Gerald Ford, from 1974 to 1977. Hinman also assisted Rockefeller in his unsuccessful campaigns for the Republican presidential nomination in 1960, 1964, and 1968.

Additionally, Hinman served on the Republican National Committee from 1959 to 1977, often as a member of the executive committee. He also served as Delegate-at-Large from New York State to the Republican National Conventions of 1960, 1964, and 1976. Following the inauguration of President Jimmy Carter in 1977, Hinman resigned from the national committee, yet remained one of Rockefeller's advisors after his withdrawal from politics.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Material in the Rockefeller family collections that provides the names, correspondence, or activities of living members of the Rockefeller family, and/or documents the net wealth of any Rockefeller family members, is restricted. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: Subseries 1 is arranged alphabetically by name or topic.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: These files contain correspondence from George Hinman to individuals on political matters that concerned Republican party politics and Governor Rockefeller's role within the party. The majority of the letters are from Hinman himself, although a significant number of letters were forwarded by another member of the Governor's staff to Hinman for acknowledgement. In these cases, the correspondence includes the copy of the letter signed by Governor Rockefeller.

Many of the files include Hinman's "memorandum for files," which are his notations on individuals, telephone conversations with political operatives, or meetings or discussions with the individual. Many prominent political individuals are represented here, including U.S. Senator and 1964 Republican presidential candidate Barry Goldwater, New York Mayor John Lindsay, President Richard Nixon, Michigan Governor George Romney, and Pennsylvania Governor William Scranton.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: This subseries is arranged alphabetically by state.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The state files consist of letters from individuals arranged by state. There is some duplication of correspondence from the general correspondence between the state files and the general correspondence files in Subseries 1.

In addition to correspondence, the State Files also contain "trip books" which were prepared by Hinman in advance of a political visit by Governor Rockefeller. The majority of the State Files also contain copies of pages from the "Congressional Quarterly" that denote races in states around the country as well as political notes from that state. The notes contain frequent updates as Hinman interacted with prominent state individuals. The Summaries contain information gathered by Hinman and his staff.

Both the State Files and Summaries are arranged alphabetically. At the end of the subserires is one file titled, Political Financial Contributors. This file is a list of individuals who pledged monetary support to Governor Rockefeller's political campaigns.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This small subseries contains a file of individuals who were recommended to serve on Governor Rockefeller's staff. Some of the individuals sought positions by sending resumes and letters of interest to Hinman, while others were recommended by other members of Governor Rockefeller's staff or friends of Hinman.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains memoranda sent to Governor Rockefeller by Hinman. The memos are entirely political in nature and deal with Governor Rockefeller's political status nationwide. Hinman indicated that many of the memos were "personal and confidential" and were to be viewed only by the Governor. They contain specific mentions of political rivals and strategies that could be implemented in future political campaigns.
